            . This hat had been on our parlour table about eight o'clock; the passage door was men. and I heard a footstep; I heared into the par<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181607100036"></xptr>lour almost directly; and there was an old hat on the chair, and the hat in question was gone.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160710-88-person642">
                  ANN 
                  MOUNTAIN
               <interp inst="t18160710-88-person642" type="surname" value="MOUNTAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160710-88-person642" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160710-88-person642" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live next door to the prosecutrix. About eight o'clock in the morning of the day in the indictment, the prisoner was coming into the house where I live, but on seeing of me, turned out again.</p>

               <p>SAMUEL MILLER. I apprehended the prisoner, on the day in the indictment, at the Princess of Wales, commonly called, Black Hell, in Wentworth-street; he had this hat on his head.</p>

               <p>JAMES ROSS. I am a batter, I can swear to my having sold that hat to the prosecutor.</p>

